---
<BaseLayout
  title="Common Questions About Restorative Reproductive Medicine"
  description="Restorative Reproductive Medicine has received both support and criticism from medical organizations. We address common questions with published evidence, acknowledge limitations, and clarify what RRM is and is not."
  canonicalUrl="https://rrmacademy.org/common-questions-about-rrm"
  ogType="article"
  publishDate="2026-03-01"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <div class="page-wrapper" data-pagefind-ignore="all">
    <div class="container container--narrow">

      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span aria-hidden="true"> &rsaquo; </span>
        <a href="/guides/">Guides</a>
        <span aria-hidden="true"> &rsaquo; </span>
        <span>Common Questions About RRM</span>
      </nav>

      <h1>Common Questions About Restorative Reproductive Medicine</h1>

      <p class="author-byline">
        By <strong>Dr. Naomi Whittaker, MD, Board-Certified OBGYN, MIGS, NFPMC, FCI</strong> &middot; <LastUpdated path="/common-questions-about-rrm/" />
      </p>

      <article class="prose">

        <p class="pillar-lead"><strong>These are the most frequently asked questions about restorative reproductive medicine, from patients seeking diagnosis and clinicians exploring the field. Answers draw on published research and established clinical practice in RRM.</strong></p>

        <!-- Q1 -->
        <h2>Does RRM delay fertility treatment?</h2>

        <p>
          The concern, raised by major professional societies, is that pursuing RRM delays treatment,
          especially for older patients.
        </p>

        <div class="evidence-block">
          <h3 class="evidence-label">The evidence</h3>
          <p>
            RRM diagnostic evaluation typically takes 1&ndash;3 months, comparable to the preparation
            timeline for an IVF cycle. Treatment can begin immediately upon diagnosis. For patients with
            conditions like endometriosis, RRM surgical treatment has shown pregnancy rates of 55.3% per
            woman <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE meta-analysis]</mark>, and a 2021 study showed a 41%
            live birth rate with RRM treatment followed by timed intercourse
            <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE JRRM]</mark>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="acknowledge-block">
          <h3 class="acknowledge-label">What we acknowledge</h3>
          <p>
            For patients over 38 or with conditions where time is critical (severe diminished ovarian
            reserve, for example), delays in any form can reduce success rates. RRM practitioners should
            counsel patients about age-related urgency and ensure patients understand all available
            options.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="position-block">
          <h3 class="position-label">RRM Academy's position</h3>
          <p>
            Informed consent means patients know all their options. We educate patients about cause-based
            approaches to reproductive health so they can ask better questions and make fully informed decisions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Q2 -->
        <h2>Is RRM only practiced for religious reasons?</h2>

        <p>
          Some critics characterize RRM as religiously motivated rather than evidence-based, noting its
          association with Catholic healthcare systems.
        </p>

        <div class="evidence-block">
          <h3 class="evidence-label">The evidence</h3>
          <p>
            While NaProTechnology was developed at the Saint Paul VI Institute (a Catholic institution),
            the medical techniques used in RRM &mdash; including excision surgery for endometriosis,
            hormonal evaluation and support, and diagnostic imaging &mdash; are standard medical practices
            used across all healthcare settings. The research supporting RRM outcomes has been published
            in mainstream peer-reviewed journals including <em>BMC Pregnancy and Childbirth</em> and
            <em>Fertility and Sterility</em>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="acknowledge-block">
          <h3 class="acknowledge-label">What we acknowledge</h3>
          <p>
            Many RRM practitioners are motivated by both clinical evidence and ethical commitments. This
            is not unique to RRM. All medical practice involves values-based decisions. The relevant
            question is whether the treatments are effective and whether patients receive complete
            informed consent.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="position-block">
          <h3 class="position-label">RRM Academy's position</h3>
          <p>
            Our courses present the clinical evidence. We serve patients of all backgrounds and beliefs.
            The reason a patient chooses RRM (whether clinical, ethical, financial, or personal) is their
            decision.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Q3 -->
        <h2>Does RRM have lower success rates than IVF?</h2>

        <p>
          Some professional society statements claim that RRM proponents exaggerate success rates and that IVF is more effective.
        </p>

        <div class="evidence-block">
          <h3 class="evidence-label">The evidence</h3>
          <p>Direct comparison is difficult because patient populations differ. Published data shows:</p>

          <div class="table-wrap">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Metric</th>
                  <th>RRM</th>
                  <th>IVF</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Live birth rate (all ages)</td>
                  <td>29% at 2 years <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                  <td>~31% per embryo transferred (HFEA 2022)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Live birth rate (under 35)</td>
                  <td>34% <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                  <td>~35% per embryo transferred, ages 18&ndash;34 (HFEA 2022)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Cost per attempt</td>
                  <td>Often insurance-covered</td>
                  <td>$15,000&ndash;$30,000 per cycle</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Multiple pregnancy rate</td>
                  <td>Population baseline</td>
                  <td>Elevated (especially multi-embryo transfer)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Preterm delivery rate</td>
                  <td>Lower <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                  <td>Higher <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="acknowledge-block">
          <h3 class="acknowledge-label">What we acknowledge</h3>
          <p>
            RRM is strongest in conditions where the underlying cause is treatable
            (endometriosis, PCOS, hormonal deficiency). Patients deserve to understand the evidence
            for all available options so they can make informed decisions with their providers.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="position-block">
          <h3 class="position-label">RRM Academy's position</h3>
          <p>
            We present comparative data so patients can have informed conversations with their doctors.
            We believe patients deserve to understand all options, including cause-based treatment.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Q4 -->
        <h2>Is it safe to skip IVF and try RRM instead?</h2>

        <p>
          The concern is that patients may forego proven treatments in favor of less proven alternatives.
        </p>

        <div class="evidence-block">
          <h3 class="evidence-label">The evidence</h3>
          <p>
            RRM treatments (surgery, medications, hormonal support) are themselves proven medical
            interventions. Excision surgery for endometriosis is considered the gold standard even in
            conventional gynecology. Hormonal evaluation and treatment for luteal phase deficiency, PCOS,
            and thyroid disorders is standard endocrine care. The "alternative" framing mischaracterizes
            RRM as outside conventional medicine when most of its component treatments are within it.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="acknowledge-block">
          <h3 class="acknowledge-label">What we acknowledge</h3>
          <p>
            Patient autonomy includes the right to choose any treatment, including IVF. No provider,
            whether RRM or conventional, should pressure patients toward or away from a specific approach.
            The ethical obligation is complete informed consent.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Q5 -->
        <h2>What does ACOG say about RRM?</h2>

        <p>
          In <mark class="cite-needed">[YEAR]</mark>, ACOG published an issue brief expressing concerns
          about RRM, particularly regarding informed consent, delays in treatment, and the restriction of
          IVF access in some institutional settings.
        </p>

        <div class="evidence-block">
          <h3 class="evidence-label">Our response</h3>
          <p>
            We share ACOG's commitment to informed consent. That is precisely why RRM Academy exists: to
            educate patients and providers so they can make fully informed decisions. We agree that
            restricting access to any evidence-based treatment, including IVF, without full informed
            consent is wrong. We also believe that presenting IVF as the only fertility treatment without
            discussing cause-based treatment options is equally incomplete informed consent.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Closing -->
        <hr />

        <p>
          Restorative reproductive medicine is not perfect. No approach to reproductive health is. But
          it represents a meaningful option for patients who want to understand why their body isn't
          functioning as expected and want treatment directed at that cause. We believe patients deserve
          education about all their options, and that's what RRM Academy provides.
        </p>

        <p><em>This content is for educational purposes only and does not constitute medical advice.</em></p>

        <div class="related-links">
          <p>Related resources:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="/what-is-rrm/">What is Restorative Reproductive Medicine?</a></li>
            <li><a href="/courses/rrm-vs-ivf/">RRM vs. Standard ART &mdash; Free Course</a></li>
            <li><a href="/library/">RRM Research Library</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p class="page-updated">Last updated: March 2026</p>
  <BackToTop />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 1.25rem + 2.5vw, 3.25rem);
    line-height: 1.2;
    letter-spacing: -0.015em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .author-byline {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  }

  .evidence-block,
  .acknowledge-block,
  .position-block {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--border-color);
    padding-left: var(--space-5);
    margin: var(--space-5) 0;
  }
  .evidence-block { border-left-color: var(--purple-300); }
  .acknowledge-block { border-left-color: var(--sand-300); }
  .position-block { border-left-color: var(--sage-300); }

  .evidence-label,
  .acknowledge-label,
  .position-label {
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--text-tertiary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .table-wrap {
    overflow-x: auto;
    margin: var(--space-6) 0;
  }
  table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  th {
    background: var(--bg-surface);
    font-weight: 600;
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    text-align: left;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border-color);
  }
  td {
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light);
    vertical-align: top;
  }
  tr:last-child td {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .cite-needed {
    background: rgba(180, 83, 9, 0.12);
    color: var(--amber-700);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0 3px;
    font-style: normal;
    font-size: 0.8em;
  }

  .related-links {
    margin-top: var(--space-10);
    padding-top: var(--space-8);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  }

  /* Prose — article body typography */
  .prose {
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }
  .prose h2 {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', 'Georgia', serif;
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-top: var(--space-10);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }
  .prose h3 {
    font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', 'Georgia', serif;
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }
  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
  }
  .prose a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 2px;
  }
  .prose a:hover {
    color: var(--purple-900);
  }
  .prose strong {
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .prose em {
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .prose ul,
  .prose ol {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-5);
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
  }
  .prose li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }
  .prose hr {
    border: none;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);
    margin: var(--space-8) 0;
  }
</style>
